point that people are trying

00:49:54.528 --> 00:49:56.020
to cope with in different ways.

00:49:56.020 --> 00:49:58.228
AUDIENCE: When you first
came to a town or city, what

00:49:58.228 --> 00:50:00.880
are some of the more
surprising indicators

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:02.740
of either civic
health or dysfunction

00:50:02.740 --> 00:50:04.545
that you found to be
consistently reliable?

00:50:04.545 --> 00:50:05.920
JAMES FALLOWS:
Does somebody have

00:50:05.920 --> 00:50:09.470
a copy of this book I
might borrow for a moment?

00:50:09.470 --> 00:50:11.834
Most of this book is
written just as narrative.

00:50:11.834 --> 00:50:13.250
Here's what we saw
in Sioux Falls.

00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:15.280
Oh, we have an intro and outro.

00:50:15.280 --> 00:50:18.790
And there's the last
part of it is called 10

00:50:18.790 --> 00:50:21.050
and 1/2 signs of civic success.

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:23.260
These are the things we
learned along the way.

00:50:23.260 --> 00:50:27.190
And most of them are
high road, for example,

00:50:27.190 --> 00:50:29.200
that we would
always ask somebody,

00:50:29.200 --> 00:50:31.210
who makes things go here.

00:50:31.210 --> 00:50:34.150
And all that mattered is
that there was an answer.

00:50:34.150 --> 00:50:36.010
And the answer in
Charleston, West Virginia

00:50:36.010 --> 00:50:40.071
was a country music singer named
Larry Gross who some of you

00:50:40.071 --> 00:50:40.570
may know.

00:50:40.570 --> 00:50:42.700
He has a program
called "Mountain Stage"

00:50:42.700 --> 00:50:46.510
on Public Radio, which has
been a fundamental fact

00:50:46.510 --> 00:50:47.890
in Charleston, West Virginia.

00:50:47.890 --> 00:50:51.760
And in Eastport, Maine it
was Captain Bob Peacock

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:54.990
and Linda Godfrey, and
some of the others.

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:57.610
So is there a local patriot?

00:50:57.610 --> 00:50:59.770
Is there a local story?

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:01.960
Do people understand
where the city

00:51:01.960 --> 00:51:05.320
is on the ascent of
mankind type of chart

00:51:05.320 --> 00:51:08.400
and why the things
we're doing now

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:10.930
will have benefits
in the future?

00:51:10.930 --> 00:51:13.810
But I say there are
10 and 1/2 signs.

00:51:13.810 --> 00:51:18.120
The half sign is, is
there a craft brewery?

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:19.770
Because a craft
brewery has become

00:51:19.770 --> 00:51:21.450
a genuine source of employment.

00:51:21.450 --> 00:51:24.090
It's a sign of a certain
kind of entrepreneur,

00:51:24.090 --> 00:51:26.190
a certain kind of
customer, and a way

00:51:26.190 --> 00:51:28.020
in which the downtown
will be expanded

00:51:28.020 --> 00:51:31.350
by bringing new areas into you.

00:51:31.350 --> 00:51:33.945
But the end of the book is 10
and 1/2 signs of civic success.

00:51:33.945 --> 00:51:36.240
So you can see it all there.

00:51:36.240 --> 00:51:38.160
AUDIENCE: Very excited
about the prospects

00:51:38.160 --> 00:51:42.660
of us progressing through
this poisoned atmosphere.

00:51:42.660 --> 00:51:45.510
But I'm wondering the
flip side of the coin,

00:51:45.510 --> 00:51:46.540
nothing's inevitable.

00:51:46.540 --> 00:51:50.100
So what would it look like
if that didn't happen?

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:53.270
Because it feels as if the whole
administration that's there

00:51:53.270 --> 00:51:55.590
is getting thinner
and thinner and just

00:51:55.590 --> 00:51:59.760
isn't enough to actually
support long-term poison.

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:03.060
But I don't want to get
my hopes too high up.

00:52:03.060 --> 00:52:05.670
JAMES FALLOWS: This is a
whole separate topic, which

00:52:05.670 --> 00:52:07.530
we can talk about offline.

00:52:07.530 --> 00:52:09.210
I think you will
see "The Atlantic"

00:52:09.210 --> 00:52:11.820
going into this with
100 articles a day

00:52:11.820 --> 00:52:15.630
about the mechanics of
the current struggle.

00:52:15.630 --> 00:52:21.360
I think it would be better
if we had a functioning

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:22.410
national government.

00:52:22.410 --> 00:52:24.134
And I think we will ultimately.

00:52:24.134 --> 00:52:26.550
Because there's things that
only a national government can

00:52:26.550 --> 00:52:31.860
do from environmental standards
to other kinds of standards

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:33.580
that hold the country together.

00:52:33.580 --> 00:52:36.270
I think the alternative
is having California

00:52:36.270 --> 00:52:39.480
be more and more on its own, and
Texas more and more on its own.

00:52:39.480 --> 00:52:41.190
And that would be
OK in various ways.

00:52:41.190 --> 00:52:44.340
But I think I'd
rather than speculate

00:52:44.340 --> 00:52:47.250
on how bad things might look
20 or 30 years from now, think

00:52:47.250 --> 00:52:50.520
about making sure people get out
to vote in the next few months

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:53.970
and that they experiment
locally to provide the fodder

00:52:53.970 --> 00:52:56.820
for the next wave of renewal.

00:52:56.820 --> 00:52:59.360
So with that, I think
we come back to center,

00:52:59.360 --> 00:53:00.370
and thank you all.

00:53:00.370 --> 00:53:02.040
Thank you all for
coming, very much.

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:04.490
[APPLAUSE]

